the experience of listening to a wide range of music. He defends, with some qualifications, the views of nineteenth-century musician and psychologist Edmund Gurney, author of The Power of Sound, who argued that musical comprehension requires only attention to the evolution of music from moment to moment.Music theory standardly misapprehends the experience and mindset of most who know and love classical music, concludes Levinson. His book is a defense of the passionate and attentive, though architectonically unconcerned, music listener.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Sep 2019) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aMusicxPsychological aspects. 0aMusical perception. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 7aMUSIC / Instruction & Study / Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501727665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501727665.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG